  {
    "client_msg_id": "e0ba8c70-5f30-4874-a700-445cebe7edd8",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "A local nonprofit that works closely with the school districts in my state recruited me and others as college mentors to lead a new coding camp, with one college mentor per class of about 30 kids. They gave us a curriculum provided by a local boot camp. The result was that the entire 9-week program was dedicated to having each kid build the same website, with a bit of flexibility for styling. I had to fight the system to give the kids in my classroom freedom to pursue the projects they actually wanted to work on.\n\nThe perception among educators seems to be that because programming is considered a STEM field, it can be effectively taught like a math class. The teacher presents the material, the kids are assigned homework problems, and the teacher grades the resulting work. This is not how anyone that I know who loves programming learned to code. In my experience, coding is much better learned the way an artist learns to paint or a writer to write. Rather than giving the kids homework assignments specially crafted to be easy to grade, we should be giving them freedom to pursue whatever projects interest them, and provide guidance and support in helping them to choose projects that are achievable and will stretch them. I find that the things I learn actually stick with me if I discover them for myself.",
    "user": "UJLHTBK0V",
    "ts": "1557773095.129000",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
